  "prompt": "How has legislation evolved to combat money laundering?",
  "response": "Legislation to combat money laundering has evolved significantly over time:\n\n1. Early Stages\n- Initial anti-money laundering (AML) laws emerged in the 1970s\n- Bank Secrecy Act (1970) in the United States was a pioneering legislation\n- Focus on reporting large cash transactions\n\n2. International Developments\n- Formation of Financial Action Task Force (FATF) in 1989\n- Establishment of international AML standards and recommendations\n- Increased global cooperation in tracking financial crimes\n\n3. Key Legislative Milestones\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001) significantly expanded AML regulations\n- Enhanced due diligence requirements\n- Increased reporting and monitoring mechanisms\n\n4. Technological Adaptations\n- Legislation addressing digital currencies and cryptocurrency transactions\n- Enhanced regulations for online financial platforms\n- Expanded definition of financial institutions\n\n5. Comprehensive Compliance Requirements\n- Mandatory customer identification programs\n- Regular risk assessments\n- Suspicious activity reporting\n- Enhanced background checks\n\n6. Global Regulatory Trends\n- Stricter international sanctions\n- Cross-border information sharing\n- Increased penalties for non-compliance\n\n7. Recent Developments\n- Advanced data analytics integration\n- Machine learning for transaction monitoring\n- More comprehensive beneficial ownership regulations\n\nThe evolution continues with ongoing technological and regulatory challenges.",
